fields.content: This composer’s A London Symphony, which he later remarked might more accurately be called a "symphony by a Londoner," is not overtly pictorial in its presentation of London. In 1953, he stated that his favorite choral work was Sancta Civitas. He wrote incidental music for an amateur dramatization in 1906 and revisited the theme in 1921 with The Shepherds of the Delectable Mountains, later incorporated into his 1951 opera. Conductors closely associated with his music include Vernon Handley, Richard Hickox, Sir Mark Elder, and Sir Andrew Davis. Some of his finest works elude conventional categorization, such as Serenade to Music, Flos Campi, and On Wenlock Edge. Near the start of the Cold War, many critics thought its pianissimo last movement depicted a nuclear-scorched wasteland. He commented to Ursula, "They don't like it, they won't like it, they don't want an opera with no heroine and no love duets—and I don't care, it's what I meant, and there it is." For 10 points, name this British composer.

wiki_sents: A London Symphony (1911–1913) which the composer later observed might more accurately be called a "symphony by a Londoner", is for the most part not overtly pictorial in its presentation of London.
In 1953 the composer said that of his choral works Sancta Civitas was his favourite.

Vaughan Williams had written incidental music for an amateur dramatisation in 1906, and had returned to the theme in 1921 with the one-act The Shepherds of the Delectable Mountains (finally incorporated, with amendments, into the 1951 opera).

Among the British conductors most closely associated with Vaughan Williams's music on disc and in concert in the generations after Boult, Sargent and Barbirolli are Vernon Handley, Richard Hickox, Sir Mark Elder and Sir Andrew Davis.

Some of his finest works elude conventional categorisation, such as the Serenade to Music (1938) for sixteen solo singers and orchestra; Flos Campi (1925) for solo viola, small orchestra, and small chorus; and his most important chamber work, in Howes's view—not purely instrumental but a song cycle—On Wenlock Edge (1909) with accompaniment for string quartet and piano.

fields.content: This polyhedron is topologically related as a part of a sequence of regular polyhedra with Schläfli symbols {3,n}, continuing into the hyperbolic plane. These points define the Euler line of the polyhedron that is analogous to the Euler line of a triangle. This can be rewritten using a dot product and a cross product, yielding. In fact, five is the minimum number of these polyhedra required to compose a cube. The three faces interior to this polyhedron are: a right triangle with edges 1, \( \sqrt{\tfrac{3}{2}} \), \( \sqrt{\tfrac{1}{2}} \); a right triangle with edges 1, \( \sqrt{\tfrac{1}{3}} \), \( \sqrt{\tfrac{1}{2}} \), \( \sqrt{\tfrac{1}{6}} \); and a right triangle with edges \( \sqrt{\tfrac{4}{3}} \), \( \sqrt{\tfrac{3}{2}} \), \( \sqrt{\tfrac{1}{6}} \). These seven line segments are all concurrent at a point called the centroid of this polyhedron. The 3-orthoscheme is a polyhedron having two right angles at each of two vertices, so another name for it is birectangular polyhedron. An orthogonal line dropped from the Monge point to any face meets that face at the midpoint of the line segment between that face's orthocenter and the foot of the altitude dropped from the opposite vertex. fields.content: Instructed by the Virginia Convention, a delegation in Philadelphia proposed a resolution for independence, foreign alliances, and a confederation of states. Two days later, delegates signed a petition to King George III affirming loyalty to the crown and imploring him to prevent further conflict. To avoid capture by advancing British forces, the assembly moved to Baltimore in the winter of 1776–77. The king refused to receive the petition. Within two weeks, Randolph was summoned back to Virginia to preside over the House of Burgesses, with Hancock succeeding him as president and Thomas Jefferson replacing him in the Virginia delegation. Amid the escalating Revolutionary War, residents of St. John's Parish in present-day Liberty County sent Lyman Hall to the gathering in Philadelphia. Hall urged the assembly to take measures for forming foreign alliances and to prepare a plan of confederation for the newly independent states. For 10 points, name this assembly that adopted the Lee Resolution on July 2, 1776, declaring independence from Britain, and unanimously agreed to the Declaration of Independence two days later.

fields.content: Near the end of the second act, main antagonist Marquis Vincent de Garmont (Bill Skarsgård) is seen standing before this painting inside the Louvre Museum, which was famously closed to the public for the filming of the scenes. The novel describes the events of the June Rebellion two years after the revolution celebrated in this painting, the same rebellion that led to its being removed from public view. The fighters are from a mixture of social classes, ranging from the bourgeoisie represented by the young man in a top hat, a student from the prestigious École Polytechnique wearing the traditional bicorne, to the revolutionary urban worker, as exemplified by the boy holding pistols. The suggestion that it was a self-portrait by Delacroix has been discounted by modern art historians. The imagery was adapted by Robert Ballagh to commemorate Ireland's independence struggle on an Irish postage stamp in 1979, the centenary of the birth of Pádraig Pearse, and the painting was used for the band Coldplay's 2008 album cover Viva la Vida or Death and All His Friends, with the words Viva La Vida written in white. An engraved version of part of the painting, along with a depiction of Delacroix, was featured on the 100 franc note from 1978 to 1995. fields.content: These species are classified under the E.C. system with four distinct numbers. The burst phase model explains the behavior of these species, which can be tracked with para-nitrophenolate formation. The Briggs-Haldane derivation assumes a low concentration of these species. A mass balance around this species, coupled with the quasi-steady state assumption, is used to define their maximum velocity. An increase in their concentration decreases the y-intercept on a Lineweaver-Burke plot, and their reaction rate is always first-order according to the Michaelis-Menten equation. Induced fit and lock-and-key models describe them. For 10 points, name these proteins whose names usually end in "ase," which catalyze biological reactions of substrates.

fields.content: As a consequence, protein engineering is an active area of research and involves attempts to create new proteins with novel properties, either through rational design or in vitro evolution. fields.content: This country alternated between civilian and military governments until January 1993, when the military government gave way to the Fourth Republic after elections in late 1992. Nana Akufo-Addo, the ruling party candidate, was narrowly defeated in the 2008 general election by John Atta Mills of the National Democratic Congress. In 2013, Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad met with Mahama to discuss strengthening the Non-Aligned Movement and co-chaired a bilateral meeting at the presidential palace Flagstaff House. Kente, a ceremonial cloth hand-woven on a horizontal treadle loom, is traditional here, with strips about 4 inches wide sewn into larger pieces. This country's Stock Exchange was the 2nd best performing in sub-Saharan Africa in 2013. UNESCO named its castles and forts as World Heritage Monuments. Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad met with Mahama in 2013 to hold discussions on strengthening the Non-Aligned Movement and also co–chair a bilateral meeting between Ghana and Iran at the Ghanaian presidential palace Flagstaff House.

Acts agrees with Paul's letters on the major outline of Paul's career: he is converted and becomes a Christian missionary and apostle, establishing new churches in Asia Minor and the Aegean and struggling to free Gentile Christians from the Jewish Law.

Western texts of Acts are 6.2–8.4% longer than Alexandrian texts, the additions tending to enhance the Jewish rejection of the Messiah and the role of the Holy Spirit, in ways that are stylistically different from the rest of Acts.

fields.content: The most common cause of hyperphosphatemia in people, dogs, and cats is kidney failure. These structures are made of crystalline calcium compounds in the form of hydroxyapatite. Calcium hydroxyapatite and calcite precipitates can be found around bacteria in alluvial topsoil. Rock deposits containing this substance can also be found in Egypt, Israel, Palestine, Western Sahara, Navassa Island, Tunisia, Togo, and Jordan, countries that have large mining industries for this material. Most other compounds of this type are only slightly soluble or are insoluble in water. Around pH 9.8 (mid-way between the second and third pKa values) the monohydrogen form of this ion, [HPO4]2−, is the only species present. In December 2012, Cominco Resources announced an updated JORC compliant resource of their Hinda project in Congo-Brazzaville of 531 million tons, making it the largest measured and indicated deposit of this substance in the world. The hard dense enamel of mammalian teeth may contain fluoroapatite, a hydroxy calcium compound where some of the hydroxyl groups have been replaced by fluoride ions. Plants take up this element through several pathways: the arbuscular mycorrhizal pathway and the direct uptake pathway. Around pH 4.7 (mid-way between the first two pKa values) the dihydrogen form of this ion, [H2PO4]−, is practically the only species present. For 10 points, name this ion that is crucial for biological processes and is often found in fertilizers.

fields.content: This figure shares his name with a historian from Halicarnassus whose Romaike Archaeologica is a source of Etruscan mythology. This god's attributes include the kantharos, a two-handled cup, as well a bassaris fox skin, which is why his followers are sometimes called bassarids. fields.content: This figure was variably known with the following epithets: Bacchus, Liber, and Bromios. However, to Julian, the myth of this god's birth (and that of Heracles) stood as an allegory for a deeper spiritual truth. Pliny believed this deity to be the historical prototype for the Roman Triumph. Another parallel can be seen in The Bacchae where this god appears before King Pentheus on charges of claiming divinity, which is compared to Jesus being interrogated by Pontius Pilate. He also notes that the grieving goddess Demeter refused to drink wine, as she states that it would be against themis for her to drink wine, which is the gift of this god, after Persephone's abduction; indicating that Hades may have been a "cover name" for the underworld version of this deity. The old man had wandered away drunk, and was found by some peasants who carried him to their king Midas (alternatively, he passed out in Midas' rose garden). For 10 points, name this god, who in the Orphic tradition, was the son of Zeus and Persephone, and was dismembered by the Titans before being reborn.

fields.content: Supporters of realism in international relations argue that the motivation of states is the quest for security, and conflicts can arise from the inability to distinguish defense from offense, called the security dilemma. Demographic theories can be grouped into Malthusian and youth bulge theories. The Marxist theory of this phenomenon states all modern instances are caused by competition for resources and markets between great (imperialist) powers, claiming these instances are a natural result of capitalism. According to philosopher Iain King, "Most instigators of conflict overrate their chances of success, while most participants underrate their chances of injury...." King asserts that "Most catastrophic military decisions are rooted in groupthink" which is faulty, but still rational. Pope Urban II in 1095, on the eve of the First Crusade, advocated Crusade as a solution to European overpopulation. Youth bulge theory has been subjected to statistical analysis by the World Bank, Population Action International, and the Berlin Institute for Population and Development. Following World War II, consensus opinion for many years amongst economists and historians was that this phenomenon can stimulate a country's economy as evidenced by the U.S's emergence from the Great Depression, though modern economic analysis has thrown significant doubt on these views. The statistical analysis of this phenomenon was pioneered by Lewis Fry Richardson following World War I. Jus in bello (right in this phenomenon), is the set of ethical rules when conducting it. For 10 points, name this phenomenon.

fields.content: This phenomenon was the subject of the 1648 Treaty of Westphalia, which ended a conflict involving the Holy Roman Empire. The concept of "total" engagement in this phenomenon was first articulated by Carl von Clausewitz in his seminal work "On this Phenomenon." The "just" theory of this phenomenon was extensively developed by thinkers like Thomas Aquinas and Hugo Grotius. fields.content: The "Dutch Process" for preparing a pigment of this color involved heaping buckets of animal manure around clay pots full of metal and acetic acid; that pigment of this color was used to make Venetian Ceruse, a cosmetic that often gave women lead poisoning. Beeswax was used in a Jasper Johns painting using this color only to depict the U.S. flag. Because of its large collection of Bauhaus buildings, part of Tel Aviv is nicknamed the "city" of this color. Joanna Hiffernan appeared in a dress of this color in three "symphonies" created by James Whistler. James Hoban designed a building named after this color whose address is 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue. Neoclassical buildings and sculptures made use of, for 10 points, what color that describes the "House" of the American President?

While most bleaches are oxidizing agents, a fewer number are reducing agents such as sodium dithionite. For example, when buying a "light" bulb, one might buy one labeled 2700K, 6000K, etc., which produce light having very different spectral distributions, and yet this will not prevent the user from identifying the color of objects that those light bulbs illuminate. fields.content: Aciclovir is built from a hydroxymethyl group bound to this compound. Cisplatin prevents a "suicide enzyme" methyltransferase from binding this compound. fields.content: In 1656 in Paris, a Mr. Jaquin extracted from the scales of the fish Alburnus alburnus so-called "pearl essence", which is a crystalline compound. This compound is not synthesized de novo; instead, it's split from the more complex molecule, guanosine, by the enzyme guanosine phosphorylase. Between 1882 and 1906, Emil Fischer determined the structure and showed that uric acid can be converted to this compound. A Fischer–Tropsch synthesis can also form this compound, along with adenine, uracil, and thymine. First, this compound gets deaminated to become xanthine. Trace amounts of this compound form by the polymerization of ammonium cyanide (NH4CN). On 8 August 2011, a NASA report suggested building blocks of DNA and RNA (this compound, adenine, and related molecules) may have formed extra-terrestrially. Facial treatments using the droppings of Japanese nightingales have been used because this compound makes the skin look paler. This compound is also found in specialized skin cells of fish called iridocytes, as well as in the reflective deposits of the eyes of deep-sea fish and some reptiles. For 10 points, name this nitrogenous base, one of the four main nucleobases found in DNA and RNA.

wiki_sents: In 1656 in Paris, a Mr. Jaquin extracted from the scales of the fish Alburnus alburnus so-called "pearl essence", which is crystalline guanine.
Guanine is not synthesized de novo[clarification needed], instead it's split from the more complex molecule, guanosine, by the enzyme guanosine phosphorylase:
Between 1882 and 1906, Emil Fischer determined the structure and also showed that uric acid can be converted to guanine.
A Fischer–Tropsch synthesis can also be used to form guanine, along with adenine, uracil, and thymine.
First, guanine gets deaminated to become xanthine.
Trace amounts of guanine form by the polymerization of ammonium cyanide (NH4CN).

On 8 August 2011, a report, based on NASA studies with meteorites found on Earth, was published suggesting building blocks of DNA and RNA (guanine, adenine and related organic molecules) may have been formed extra-terrestrially in outer space.
Facial treatments using the droppings, or guano, from Japanese nightingales have been used in Japan and elsewhere, because the guanine in the droppings makes the skin look paler.

Guanine is also found in specialized skin cells of fish called iridocytes (e.g., the sturgeon), as well as being present in the reflective deposits of the eyes of deep-sea fish and some reptiles, such as crocodiles and chameleons.

fields.content: This molecule was first isolated from guano by Julius Bodo Unger in 1844. It is synthesized in the body through the deamination of adenine and is a key component in the biosynthesis of GMP. This molecule pairs with cytosine through three hydrogen bonds in the structure of DNA. It is one of the two purine nucleobases found in nucleic acids. This molecule is essential for the coding, decoding, and expression of genes. It is also found in RNA, where it pairs with cytosine. This molecule is abbreviated as "G" in genetic sequences. It is one of the four main nucleobases in DNA, along with adenine, thymine, and cytosine. For 10 points, name this nucleobase.

fields.content: According to MĀ 204 (but not MN 26), as well as the Theravāda Vinaya, an Ekottarika-āgama text, the Dharmaguptaka Vinaya, the Mahīśāsaka Vinaya, and the Mahāvastu, this figure taught the "first sermon", also known as the "Benares sermon". Another epithet, used at inscriptions throughout South and Southeast Asia, is Maha sramana, "great sramana" (ascetic, renunciate). However, Jain sources also claim his allegiance, and it is likely he supported various religious groups, not just his own sangha exclusively. This process takes place through the five skandhas, "aggregates", five groups of physical and mental processes: form (rupa), sensations (vedana), perceptions (samjna), mental activity (sankhara), and consciousness (vijnana). According to all major versions surveyed by Anālayo, Mahāprajāpatī Gautamī, his step-mother, is initially turned down by him after requesting ordination for her and some other women. For 10 points, name this religious figure who is central to a major world religion.

fields.content: A piece of Canada Balsam is placed in between two specimens of this mineral to create the Nicol Prism. Ancient ooids (oh-oy-ds) are often composed from the "seas" of this substance that characterize the Paleozoic and the early Mesozoic Eras. The rock onyx is often confused for the "banded" form of this mineral found in Mexican mines. The highly unstable polymorph vaterite is converted to this mineral when it is exposed to water at low temperature. Erasmus Bartholin first observed "double refraction" in a variety of this mineral known as Iceland spar. Aragonite is a polymorph of this mineral which can be found in mineral springs. fields.content: The birefringent effect using this mineral was first described by the Danish scientist Rasmus Bartholin in 1669. Trilobites, which became extinct a quarter billion years ago, had unique compound eyes that used clear crystals of this mineral to form the lenses. This mineral is often the primary constituent of the shells of marine organisms, such as plankton, red algae, sponges, brachiopods, echinoderms, serpulids, bryozoa, and some bivalves. Large quantities of this mineral in Iceland are concentrated in the Helgustadir mine. This mineral exhibits several twinning types that add to the observed habits. Most common are scalenohedra, with faces in the hexagonal {2 1 1} or {2 1 4} directions, and rhombohedral, with faces in the {1 0 1} or {1 0 4} directions. Cleavage of this mineral is given as "perfect on {1 0 1 1}" in morphological coordinates and "perfect on {1 0 1 4}" in structural units. For 10 points, name this mineral that at a wavelength of about 590 nm has ordinary and extraordinary refractive indices of 1.658 and 1.486.

wiki_sents: The birefringent effect (using calcite) was first described by the Danish scientist Rasmus Bartholin in 1669.
Trilobites, which became extinct a quarter billion years ago, had unique compound eyes that used clear calcite crystals to form the lenses.

Calcite is often the primary constituent of the shells of marine organisms, such as plankton (such as coccoliths and planktic foraminifera), the hard parts of red algae, some sponges, brachiopods, echinoderms, some serpulids, most bryozoa, and parts of the shells of some bivalves (such as oysters and rudists).
Large quantities of calcite in Iceland are concentrated in the Helgustadir mine.
Calcite exhibits several twinning types that add to the observed habits.

Most common are scalenohedra, with faces in the hexagonal {2 1 1} directions (morphological unit cell) or {2 1 4} directions (structural unit cell); and rhombohedral, with faces in the {1 0 1} or {1 0 4} directions (the most common cleavage plane).
As an example, calcite cleavage is given as "perfect on {1 0 1 1}" in morphological coordinates and "perfect on {1 0 1 4}" in structural units.
At a wavelength of about 590 nm, calcite has ordinary and extraordinary refractive indices of 1.658 and 1.486, respectively.

fields.content: This mineral can exhibit a phenomenon known as birefringence, where it splits light into two rays with different velocities. It is a primary constituent of the rock formations known as travertine and tufa. This mineral reacts with hydrochloric acid to produce carbon dioxide gas, a property used in geological field tests. It is the defining mineral for a hardness of 3 on the Mohs scale. This mineral often forms rhombohedral crystals and can be found in stalactites and stalagmites in caves. It is a major component of limestone and marble. This mineral is also known for its double refraction properties. For 10 points, name this common carbonate mineral with the chemical formula CaCO3.

fields.content: The man on the left of this painting has a concave pose very similar to that of a Roman cameo of Augustus riding on a Capricorn. A figure on the right of this painting places his right arm around a woman in order to touch an infant, leading many scholars to identify the pair as Mary and Jesus. Frank Lynn Meshberger argued that the shape of a human brain is created in this painting by the mass of drapery and figures on the right. To the right of this painting is the scene of the water being divided from the earth. The title man in this painting is shown after formation and enlivenment but before animation. For 10 points, name this scene painted by Michelangelo for the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel where God is about to touch the first man's finger.

fields.content: This cameo is now at Alnwick Castle, Northumberland. In 2015, the Belvedere Torso was displayed with Michelangelo's sketch in the "Defining Beauty: The Body in Ancient Greek Art" show at the British Museum in London. The right side of the page was sketched in 1508 with black chalk, and is a study of a limp hand, before it is ignited with the gift of life from another figure. Among the most famous paintings on the ceiling are scenes from the Garden of Eden, the Deluge, the Prophet Jeremiah, and the Cumaean Sibyl. The inspiration for Michelangelo's treatment of the subject may come from a medieval hymn, "Veni Creator Spiritus", which asks the 'finger of the paternal right hand' to give the faithful speech. For 10 points, name this scene from the Sistine Chapel ceiling.

fields.content: The gateway to the Mediterranean Sea from the Atlantic Ocean, where the southernmost tip of Spain and the northernmost of Morocco face each other, is classically referred to as the Pillars of this mythological figure, owing to the story that he set up two massive spires of stone to stabilize the area. After the 4th century BCE, this figure became identified with the Phoenician God Melqart. Several ancient cities were named Heraclea in his honor. According to Herodotus, a line of 22 Kings of Lydia descended from this figure and Omphale. Yet another episode of his female affairs that stands out was when he carried away the oxen of Geryon, he also visited the country of the Scythians. fields.content: This institution's history entered a more mature phase under the librarianship of Aristophanes of Byzantium. Meanwhile, the scholar and poet Callimachus compiled the Pinakes, a 120-book catalogue of various authors and all their known works. fields.content: The use of this phenomenon in warfare has a long history. The Byzantine fleet used a specific type of it to attack ships and men. Controlled burns are instances of this phenomenon ignited by government agencies under less dangerous weather conditions. The glow of a flame is complex. In many cases, such as the burning of organic matter, for example wood, or the incomplete combustion of gas, incandescent solid particles called soot produce the familiar red-orange glow of this phenomenon. Methods to achieve this include balancing the input of fuel and oxidizer to stoichiometric proportions, increasing fuel and oxidizer input in this balanced mix, increasing the ambient temperature so the phenomenon's own heat is better able to sustain combustion, or providing a catalyst, a non-reactant medium in which the fuel and oxidizer can more readily react. When this phenomenon removes protective vegetation, heavy rainfall can contribute to increased soil erosion by water. This loss of nitrogen caused by this phenomenon produces a long-term reduction in the fertility of the soil, which can be recovered as atmospheric nitrogen is fixed and converted to ammonia by natural phenomena such as lightning or by leguminous plants such as clover, peas, and green beans. fields.content: CCT is a group II chaperonin, a large protein complex that assists in the folding of other proteins. A meshwork of these filaments marks the forward edge of a moving cell, and their polymerization pushes the cell membrane forward in protrusions called lamellipodia. The bacterial protein MreB polymerizes into thin non-helical filaments and occasionally into helical structures similar to F-actin. Following up on the discovery of Ilona Banga & Szent-Györgyi in 1941 that coagulation only occurs in some myosin extractions and was reversed upon the addition of ATP, Straub identified and purified this protein from those myosin preparations that did coagulate. This myosin forms polar bonds with monomers of this protein, giving rise to a configuration that looks like arrows with feather fletchings along its shaft, where the shaft is this protein and the fletchings are the myosin. These binding proteins are typically regulated by various cellular signals to control the assembly dynamics of this protein in different cellular locations. fields.content: This protein was first isolated by Bruno Ferenc Straub in 1942 from rabbit muscle. It interacts with myosin to facilitate cellular movements and is essential for processes like cytokinesis and cell motility. This protein exists in two forms: globular (G) and filamentous (F). fields.content: Conformational protein folding is usually much faster (typically 10–100 ms) than cis-trans isomerization (10–100 s). The hydrolysis of these structures in water releases 8–16 kJ/mol (2–4 kcal/mol) of Gibbs energy. However, X-Pro peptide groups tend to have a roughly 30:1 ratio, presumably because the symmetry between the Cα and Cδ atoms of proline makes the cis and trans isomers nearly equal in energy. A nonnative isomer of some peptide groups can disrupt the conformational folding significantly, either slowing it or preventing it from occurring until the native isomer is reached. The dihedral angle associated with the peptide group (defined by the four atoms Cα–C'–N–Cα) is denoted ω; ω = 0° for the cis isomer and ω = 180° for the trans isomer. Both mechanisms for lowering the activation energy have been observed in peptidyl prolyl isomerases (PPIases), which catalyze the cis-trans isomerization of X-Pro peptide groups. The amide bond is synthesized when the carboxyl group of one amino acid reacts with the amino group of another, releasing a molecule of water in a dehydration synthesis reaction. fields.content: Other examples of multiplicative squares include: Latin squares, and since for each of these squares the middle term may be arbitrarily placed in the main diagonal or the skew diagonal (and correspondingly along the skew diagonal or the main diagonal for the Latin squares), we can construct a total of 2 × (n - 1)!. The Green–Tao theorem implies that there are arbitrarily large squares consisting of primes. From the 13th century onwards, these constructs were increasingly put to occult purposes. In general, for a square of any order n, there will be 4(n - 1) border cells, which are to be filled using 2(n - 1) bone numbers. Thus, the diagonal sums will be equal if we have βs in the main diagonal and α, β, γ in the skew diagonal. It is possible to circularly shift the rows by more than one cell to create the Greek and Latin square. fields.content: This phenomenon presents a running narrative rather than exclusively visual imagery. It is discussed in the Talmud, Tractate Berachot 55–60. In the Mandukya Upanishad, part of the Veda scriptures of Indian Hinduism, it is one of three states that the soul experiences during its lifetime, the other two being the waking state and the sleep state. "Oneironaut" is a term sometimes used for those who lucidly experience it. Gudea, the king of the Sumerian city-state of Lagash (reigned c. 2144–2124 BCE), rebuilt the temple of Ningirsu as the result of experiencing this phenomenon in which he was told to do so. Gudea, the king of the Sumerian city-state of Lagash (reigned c. 2144–2124 BCE), rebuilt the temple of Ningirsu as the result of a dream in which he was told to do so.

Dreams of absent-minded transgression (DAMT) are dreams wherein the dreamer absent-mindedly performs an action that he or she has been trying to stop (one classic example is of a quitting smoker having dreams of lighting a cigarette).
Many later graphic artists have depicted dreams, including Japanese woodblock artist Hokusai (1760–1849) and Western European painters Rousseau (1844–1910), Picasso (1881–1973), and Dali (1904–1989).

fields.content: Generally, if the Blessed Sacrament is reserved in the church, it is customary to acknowledge the Lord's presence with a brief act of worship on entering or leaving the building – normally, a gesture in the direction of the place of reservation. Since this gesture is, per se, an act of adoration, the general liturgical norms no longer make any distinction between the mode of adoring Christ reserved in the tabernacle or exposed upon the altar. In the Tridentine Mass this gesture is made on any day on which the Creed is recited at Mass, as well as at several other points. The present Catholic liturgical books exclude this gesture to a bishop during the liturgy: "A gesture, made by bending the right knee to the ground, signifies adoration, and therefore it is reserved for the Most Blessed Sacrament, as well as for the Holy Cross from the solemn adoration during the liturgical celebration on Good Friday until the beginning of the Easter Vigil." In the Maronite Catholic Church, there is an evocative ceremony of this gesture on the feast of Pentecost. In 328 BC, Alexander the Great introduced into his court-etiquette some form of this gesture already in use in Persia, a modification to the tradition of Proskynesis. Since in many Anglican, Roman Catholic and Western Orthodox Churches the Blessed Sacrament is normally present behind the altar, this gesture is usual when arriving or passing in front of the altar at the communion rail. The General Instruction of the Roman Missal lays down the following rules for this gesture during Mass. For 10 points, name this act of worship that involves bending the right knee to the ground.

His skies played a particularly important part, from the blue skies and gray clouds with bright sunlit borders (a sight often called in France "a Poussin sky") to illustrate scenes of tranquility and the serenity of faith, such as the Landscape with Saint John on Patmos, painted in the late 1630s before his departure for Paris; or extremely dark, turbulent and threatening, as a setting for tragic events, as in his Landscape with Pyramus and Thisbe (1651).

fields.content: The model for their mutual articulation lay in this man's principle of the "separation of the elements," first outlined in "The Modern Theatre Is the Epic Theatre" (1930). What he took from Piscator "is fairly plain, and he acknowledged it," Willett suggests. His theatre combined popular themes with avant-garde experimentation to create a modernist realism contrasting psychological and socialist varieties. In 1925, his publishers provided him with Elisabeth Hauptmann to complete his collection of poems, Devotions for the Home (Hauspostille, published in January 1927). Hauptmann, Margarete Steffin, Emil Burri, Ruth Berlau, and others worked with him to produce teaching plays, creating a new dramaturgy for participants rather than passive audiences. He is a dramatist because his language is felt physically and in the round. His most significant contribution was adapting the unfinished episodic comic novel Schweik, which he described as a "montage from the novel." For 10 points, name this playwright.

fields.content: A god who lived in this realm holds a container of jewels symbolizing his fertility, uses a mount called Makara, and was often paired with a god of truth and justice named Mitra. fields.content: The XENON research project uses a dual phase time projection chamber to search for this component, whose distribution is plotted on a NavarroFrenkWhite profile. The cusp-core problem has led to the suggestion that this component is self-interacting. Plots of orbital velocities of bodies against radial distance on a galactic rotation curve lead to the inference of this component, which Fritz Zwicky postulated after studying the Coma Cluster. Mordehai Milgrom developed MOND, or Modified Newtonian Dynamics, as an alternative to this entity. Axions are candidates for its "cold" form, while its "hot," ultra-relativistic form would be contributed from neutrinos. fields.content: Numerical simulations of structure formation in an expanding universe lead to the empirical NFW (Navarro–Frenk–White) profile. It has become conventional to refer to the mass of a certain structure at a fiducial point that encloses an overdensity 200 times greater than the critical density of the universe, though mathematically the profile extends beyond this notational point. Higher resolution computer simulations are better described by the Einasto profile. Numerical simulations of CDM structure formation have been found to proceed as follows: A small volume with small perturbations initially expands with the expansion of the Universe. At all masses, there is a marked tendency for structures with higher spin to be in denser regions and thus to be more strongly clustered. For 10 points, name this structure whose density drops off with distance from the galactic center.

fields.content: This animal, known as the first people by some Plains indigenous peoples, was bred with cattle by ranchers to produce "cattalo" or "beefalo." The Wood Buffalo Park population of this animal was determined to be crossbreeds between two subspecies, but their predominant genetic makeup was that of the expected "wood" variety. These subspecies are B. b. athabascae and B. b. bison. From the same Greek word boubalos, we also get the Bubal hartebeest. A study by Derr noted that this animal seems to be adapting successfully despite an apparent genetic bottleneck. Additionally, without conservationists, the Texas State Herd of this animal would have likely gone extinct due to a severe population bottleneck. fields.content: While searching for oil off this island's coast, Exxon drilled the world's longest borehole in 2011. After visiting a prison colony on this island, Anton Chekhov wrote his only work of non-fiction, a sociological piece criticizing the penal system. Five auspicious events, called the panch kalyanak ("PUNCH" cull-YAH-nuk), occur during the lifetimes of these people, including their attainment of kevaljnana (KEH-vul-NYAN), or perfect knowledge. fields.content: A metric q will have a form of this property if there exists some constant b such that for all pair of points c and d, the metric of "q of c d" is less than "b times q of c d"; that is the Lifshitz form of this property. A function with this property within a closed and bounded interval will attain a minimum and maximum at least once by the extreme value theorem. Though every differentiable function has this property, the converse does not hold - as exemplified by the Weierstrass function being not differentiable, despite having this. Both the Heaviside step and the absolute value functions only have the "piecewise" form of this property since there are "jumps" at the origin. For 10 points, name this property that allows one to draw a function without lifting.

fields.answer: continuity [or continuous; accept Lifshitz continuous or continuity or piecewise continuous or continuity]

fields.content: Amongst late 20th-century British published political works of this type, those of Richard Crossman, Tony Benn, and Alan Clark are representative, with Clark's being more indiscreet, in the tradition of Chips Channon. Both prompted long-running satirical features in the magazine Private Eye: the former entitled Mrs Wilson's Diary in reference to Mary Wilson, wife of Prime Minister Harold Wilson, the latter entitled The Secret Diary of John Major Aged 47¾ and written as a pastiche of the Adrian Mole works from the perspective of then-Prime Minister John Major. One of the earliest printed fictional works of this type was the humorous Diary of a Nobody by George Grossmith and his brother Weedon. A war work of this type is a regularly updated official record of a military unit's administration and activities during wartime maintained by an officer in the unit. fields.content: This author is credited with the first use of the interlocking three-line rhyme scheme known as terza rima. He did not pay a fine imposed on him, partly because he believed in his innocence and partly because his assets in Florence had been seized by the Black Guelphs. fields.content: This enzyme is crucial in the life cycle of retroviruses, where the tRNA primer is unwound between 14 and 22 nucleotides and forms a base-paired duplex with the viral RNA at PBS. The first process involves the synthesis of viral DNA from viral RNA, which then forms newly made complementary DNA strands. Two RNA genomes are packaged into each retrovirus particle, but, after an infection, each virus generates only one provirus. This enzyme has a high error rate when transcribing RNA into DNA since it has no proofreading ability. The fact that the PBS is located near the 5’ terminus of viral RNA is unusual because this enzyme synthesizes DNA from the 3’ end of the primer in the 5’ to 3’ direction. There are three different replication systems during the life cycle of a retrovirus. This enzyme has three sequential biochemical activities: RNA-dependent DNA polymerase activity, ribonuclease H (RNase H), and DNA-dependent DNA polymerase activity. In addition to the transcription function, it has a domain belonging to the RNase H family, which is vital to their replication. This enzyme is used by viruses such as HIV and hepatitis B to replicate their genomes, by retrotransposon mobile genetic elements to proliferate within the host genome, and by eukaryotic cells to extend telomeres. For 10 points, name this enzyme that Valerian Dolja argues has played a central role in the evolution of cellular life.

The first process is the reverse transcriptase synthesis of viral DNA from viral RNA, which then forms newly made complementary DNA strands.
Two RNA genomes are packaged into each retrovirus particle, but, after an infection, each virus generates only one provirus.
Reverse transcriptase has a high error rate when transcribing RNA into DNA since, unlike most other DNA polymerases, it has no proofreading ability.

The fact that the PBS is located near the 5’ terminus of viral RNA is unusual because reverse transcriptase synthesize DNA from 3’ end of the primer in the 5’ to 3’  direction (with respect to the newly synthesized DNA strand).
There are three different replication systems during the life cycle of a retrovirus.
Retroviral RT has three sequential biochemical activities: RNA-dependent DNA polymerase activity, ribonuclease H (RNase H), and DNA-dependent DNA polymerase activity.
In addition to the transcription function, retroviral reverse transcriptases have a domain belonging to the RNase H family, which is vital to their replication.

Reverse transcriptases are used by viruses such as HIV and hepatitis B to replicate their genomes, by  retrotransposon mobile genetic elements to proliferate within the host genome, and by eukaryotic cells to extend the telomeres at the ends of their linear chromosomes.
Valerian Dolja of Oregon State argues that viruses, due to their diversity, have played an evolutionary role in the development of cellular life, with reverse transcriptase playing a central role.

fields.content: This enzyme was first discovered independently by Howard Temin and David Baltimore in 1970. It is encoded by the pol gene in retroviruses. This enzyme is crucial for the replication of retroviruses, including HIV, by synthesizing DNA from an RNA template. It is targeted by antiretroviral drugs such as zidovudine (AZT) and tenofovir. This enzyme's activity is essential for the integration of viral DNA into the host genome. It has a high error rate, leading to rapid mutation and evolution of the virus. This enzyme is used in molecular biology techniques like RT-PCR to study gene expression. It is a key component in the life cycle of retroviruses. For 10 points, name this enzyme.

fields.content: In response to British requests and sensitivities of the French-Canadian population, Canada, despite being at war with the Axis since 1939, maintained full diplomatic relations with this regime until early November 1942, when Case Anton led to its complete occupation by the Germans. Reynaud was arrested in September 1940 by this government and sentenced to life imprisonment in 1941, before the opening of the Riom Trial. Admiral François Darlan initiated co-operation with the Allies, who recognised Darlan's self-nomination as High Commissioner of France for North and West Africa. On 24 December 1941 Free French forces on three corvettes, supported by a submarine, landed and seized control of Saint Pierre and Miquelon on orders from Charles de Gaulle without reference to any of the Allied commanders. In part, this regime's virulent Anglophobia was due to its leaders' personal dislike of the British, as Marshal Pétain, Pierre Laval, and Admiral François Darlan were all Anglophobes. Roosevelt and Churchill accepted Darlan, rather than de Gaulle, as the French leader in North Africa. For 10 points, name this regime, which has three main periods distinguished in its historiography.

fields.content: After the Bar Kokhba revolt, the population in Judaea, significantly reduced in size, made efforts to recover but never fully regained its previous strength. Efforts by these and other groups over the past 25 years have led to a trend known as the Baal teshuva movement, where secular members become more religiously observant, though demographic implications are unknown. Genetic Y-DNA analyses in the 2000s established a partially Middle-Eastern origin for a portion of the male Lemba population. Another argument is that religious leaders changed the law of patrilineal descent to matrilineal descent due to widespread rape by Roman soldiers. Some scholars prefer translating Ioudaios as "Judean" in the Bible to denote the community's origins and prevent antisemitic eisegesis. In modern times, antisemitic themes are often conflated with anti-Zionist publications and pronouncements of Islamic movements like Hezbollah and Hamas, and agencies of Iran and Turkish Refah Partisi. In the Papal States, which existed until 1870, this group was required to live in specified neighborhoods called ghettos. The First Jewish-Roman War (66–73 CE) culminated in the destruction of Jerusalem and the Second Temple. For 10 points, name this ethnic and religious group.

wiki_sents: After the Bar Kokhba revolt, the Jewish population in Judaea, now significantly reduced in size, made efforts to recover from the revolt's devastating effects, but never fully regained its previous strength.

As a result of the efforts by these and other Jewish groups over the past 25 years, there has been a trend (known as the Baal teshuva movement) for secular Jews to become more religiously observant, though the demographic implications of the trend are unknown.

Views on the Lemba have changed and genetic Y-DNA analyses in the 2000s have established a partially Middle-Eastern origin for a portion of the male Lemba population but have been unable to narrow this down further.
Another argument is that the rabbis changed the law of patrilineal descent to matrilineal descent due to the widespread rape of Jewish women by Roman soldiers.
Some scholars prefer translating Ioudaios as "Judean" in the Bible since it is more precise, denotes the community's origins and prevents readers from engaging in antisemitic eisegesis.

In modern times, it has become commonplace for standard antisemitic themes to be conflated with anti-Zionist publications and pronouncements of Islamic movements such as Hezbollah and Hamas, in the pronouncements of various agencies of the Islamic Republic of Iran, and even in the newspapers and other publications of Turkish Refah Partisi.
In the Papal States, which existed until 1870, Jews were required to live only in specified neighborhoods called ghettos.
The First Jewish-Roman War (66–73 CE) culminated in the destruction of Jerusalem and the Second Temple.

fields.content: In this technique, overtones are false signals that appear at twice the amount of a very strong signal. Aldehydes are easily identified by this technique due to bumps on the right hand side of the alkane peak. This technique detects stretching and scissoring of bonds in water molecules. fields.content: An alternate method for acquiring spectra is the "dispersive" or "scanning monochromator" method. The fact that CRDS is based on the measurements of photon life-times (and not the laser intensity) makes it needless for any calibration and comparison with a reference. The radiation passes through the crystal and only interacts with the sample at the interface between the two materials. For molecules with N atoms, linear molecules have 3N – 5 vibrational modes, whereas nonlinear molecules have 3N – 6 vibrational modes. In systems like silicon and germanium, the decay of the anti-symmetric stretch mode of interstitial oxygen involves the symmetric stretch mode with a strong isotope dependence. Another method is electron energy loss spectroscopy (EELS), where the energy absorbed is provided by an inelastically scattered electron. For 10 points, name this technique that analyzes vibrational modes that are IR-inactive but appear in inelastic neutron scattering using EELS.

fields.content: This technique can be used to study the vibrational modes of molecules, as demonstrated by the analysis of the amide I and II bands in proteins. It often employs a Michelson interferometer in its Fourier-transform variant. This method can identify functional groups by their characteristic absorption bands, such as the carbonyl stretch around 1700 cm⁻¹. It is commonly used to analyze organic compounds and can distinguish between different isomers. This technique is particularly useful in identifying the presence of hydroxyl groups, which absorb strongly around 3200-3600 cm⁻¹. fields.content: Atwood's inspiration for the Republic of Gilead came from her study of early American Puritans while at a prestigious university, which she attended on a Woodrow Wilson Fellowship. Fitting with her statements that this novel is a work of speculative fiction, not science fiction, Atwood's novel offers a satirical view of various social, political, and religious trends of the United States in the 1980s. Atwood argues that all of the scenarios offered in this novel have actually occurred in real life—in an interview she gave regarding her later novel Oryx and Crake, Atwood maintains that "As with this novel, I didn't put in anything that we haven't already done, we're not already doing, we're seriously trying to do, coupled with trends that are already in progress...". The protagonist portrays Jezebels as attractive and educated; they may be unsuitable as Handmaids due to temperament. For 10 points, name this dystopian novel by Margaret Atwood.

fields.content: Illumination techniques and trends under this polity were often dependent upon script style. Islamic philosophy during this era was neither necessarily concerned with religious issues, nor exclusively produced by Muslims. This expansion and establishment of the book arts culminated in a formative period of the Islamic manuscript tradition. In the 9th century, this polity created an army loyal only to their rulers, composed of non-Arab origin people, known as Mamluks. Al-Ukhaidir Fortress is a fine example of this type of building, which has stables, living quarters, and a mosque, all surrounding inner courtyards. Several embassies from the rulers of this polity to the Chinese court have been recorded in the Old Book of Tang, the most important of these being those of Abul Abbas al-Saffah, the first ruler; his successor Abu Jafar; and Harun al-Rashid. The caliph's immediate family was also executed, with the lone exceptions of his youngest son who was sent to Mongolia, and a daughter who became a slave in the harem of Hulagu. The central government of this polity was weakened after the "Anarchy at Samarra" (861–870). For 10 points, name this Islamic caliphate that ruled from Baghdad.

The House of Wisdom, a renowned intellectual center, was established during this caliphate's rule. The caliphate's power began to wane after the Battle of Talas and the rise of regional dynasties like the Tulunids and Saffarids. fields.content: Ladderane molecules are comprised of repeats of this kind of molecule. Large examples of these compounds have steric interactions between flagpole hydrogens, while small examples of them exhibit so-called "banana bonds" due to angle strain. fields.content: Many people consider blood to have a metallic flavor. Other possible fat flavor receptors have been identified. The CaSR receptor is commonly found in the gastrointestinal tract, kidneys, and brain. It is only during ingestion that the fatty acids that make up triglycerides are hydrolyzed into fatty acids via lipases. G protein-coupled receptors free fatty acid receptor 4 (GPR120) and to a lesser extent Free fatty acid receptor 1 (GPR40) have been linked to fat flavor, as their absence resulted in reduced preference for linoleic and oleic acid, and decreased neuronal response to oral fatty acids. Pungency (piquancy or hotness) had traditionally been considered a sixth basic flavor. Some plant-derived compounds that provide this sensation are capsaicin from chili peppers, piperine from black pepper, gingerol from ginger root, and allyl isothiocyanate from horseradish. For 10 points, name this sensory perception.

fields.content: This poet's close friend Al Alvarez said of her later work: "Her case is complicated by the fact that, in her mature work, she deliberately used the details of her everyday life as raw material for her art." She seemed to be standing at a banquet like Timon, crying, "Uncover, dogs, and lap!" She took a job as a receptionist in the psychiatric unit of Massachusetts General Hospital and attended creative writing seminars by poet Robert Lowell, also attended by Anne Sexton and George Starbuck. In mid-1962, she and her husband began to keep bees, which would be the subject of many of her poems. She told the story of her first suicide in sweet and loving detail, and her description in her semi-autobiographical novel is just that same story. Radical feminist poet Robin Morgan published the poem "Arraignment", accusing her husband of her battery and murder. These pills were sold in England under a different name, and although her husband did not name the pills explicitly, he claimed a new doctor had prescribed them to her without realizing she had taken them before with adverse effects. At Newnham, she studied with Dorothea Krook, whom she held in high regard. Her semi-autobiographical novel was published in 1963. In his 1972 book on suicide, The Savage God, Al Alvarez claimed that her suicide was an unanswered cry for help. Development of this structure begins with the establishment of the eye fields mediated by the SHH and SIX3 proteins, with subsequent development of the optic vesicles regulated by the PAX6 and LHX2 proteins. The neural part of this structure consists of several layers of neurons interconnected by synapses and is supported by an outer layer of pigmented epithelial cells. This non-invasive technique allows one to obtain a 3D volumetric or high resolution cross-sectional tomogram of the fine structures of this part of the eye, with histologic quality. For 10 points, name this part of the eye, which includes the fovea and extends to the peripheral regions.

Retinal development begins with the establishment of the eye fields mediated by the SHH and SIX3 proteins, with subsequent development of the optic vesicles regulated by the PAX6 and LHX2 proteins.

[citation needed] Around the fovea extends the central retina for about 6 mm and then the peripheral retina.

fields.content: This structure contains a layer of cells known as the outer nuclear layer, which houses the cell bodies of photoreceptors. The fovea, a small depression in this structure, is responsible for sharp central vision. This structure's pigment epithelium plays a crucial role in the visual cycle by regenerating photopigments. The macula, located near the center of this structure, is essential for tasks requiring detailed vision, such as reading. This structure converts light into neural signals through its photoreceptor cells, rods, and cones. It is part of the eye that sends visual information to the brain via the optic nerve. For 10 points, name this light-sensitive layer at the back of the eye.

fields.content: The only novel of James Frazer, the author of The Golden Bough, recounts the slaying of this kind of creature. A snake created when the blood from the remains of one of these figures mixed with sand later killed the Argonaut Mopsus. The king of the island of Seriphos, Polydectes, demanded that a hero who failed to provide him any horses instead kill one of these creatures. Chrysaor was the son of one of these beings. A hero stole the single eye shared by their sisters, the Graeae, in order to find one of them. Two of them, Stheno and Euryale, were immortal, while their mortal sister's remains adorned the aegis after her death. For 10 points, Perseus used a mirrored shield to avoid the petrifying gaze of Medusa, who was what kind of creature?

fields.content: However, Euripides, in his tragedy Ion, has a character say that Athena's aegis was made from the skin of a creature, the offspring of Gaia, who Gaia had brought forth as an ally for her children the Giants and who Athena had killed during the Gigantomachy. Stheno and Euryale were immortal, whereas their sister was mortal. According to Apollodorus' version of their story, Perseus was ordered by Polydectes to bring back the head of this mortal sister. As Hector pursues the fleeing Achaeans, "exulting in his might," Homer describes the Trojan hero as having eyes like "the eyes of this creature." Blood from this creature was said to have both the power to heal and harm. The faces of Archaic depictions of these creatures are particularly distinctive, typically with large menacing eyes, tripartite scroll-like noses, wide mouths with rictus-like grins, lolling tongues, fangs, and/or tusks. For 10 points, name this creature whose location near the Hyperboreans is unclear according to Pindar.

wiki_sents: However, Euripides, in his tragedy Ion, has a character say that Athena's aegis was made from the skin of the Gorgon, the offspring of Gaia, who Gaia had brought forth as an ally for her children the Giants and who Athena had killed during the Gigantomachy.
Stheno and Euryale were immortal, whereas Medusa was mortal.
According to Apollodorus' version of their story, Perseus was ordered by Polydectes (his enemy) to bring back the head of Medusa.
As Hector pursues the fleeing Achaeans, "exulting in his might" ... ever slaying the hindmost", Homer describes the Trojan hero as having eyes like "the eyes of the Gorgon".
Gorgon blood was said to have both the power to heal and harm.

The faces of Archaic Gorgons are particularly distinctive, typically with large menacing eyes, tripartite scroll-like (volute) noses, wide mouths with rictus-like grins, lolling tongues, fangs and/or tusks (Figs.
However, whether Pindar means to imply that the Gorgons lived near the Hyperboreans is unclear.

fields.content: A lesser-known myth involving these creatures tells of their encounter with the hero Aristomenes, who was said to have used a mirror to avoid their deadly gaze. In another myth, these creatures were daughters of the primordial sea deities Phorcys and Ceto. One of these creatures was transformed into her monstrous form by Athena as punishment for desecrating her temple. The most famous of these creatures was beheaded by Perseus, who used her head as a weapon. This creature's head was later affixed to Athena's shield, the Aegis. For 10 points, name these mythological sisters, one of whom had snakes for hair and could turn people to stone with her gaze.
